[{"id":30248,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Optical activity is the ability of a substance to rotate the plane of polarisation of a beam of light that is passed through it.A compound to be said as optically active is only if it has to have an asymmetric chiral carbon centre (the carbon is said to be chiral if they have different substituents attached).</p><p>The optically active substances that rotate the plane of polarisation of the light towards the right are known as right-handed or dextrorotatory. It can be Indicated by including (+) or ‘D’ before the compound name.</p><p>Substances that rotate the plane of polarisation of the light toward the left are known as left-handed or laevorotatory. It can be Indicated by including (-) or ‘L’ before the compound name</p><p>The reaction is as follows,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>chlorobutane</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>→</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>8</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> </p><p> <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>8</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> will give four isomers of which one is optically inactive. Their structures are as follows,</p><p> </p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0df55944-2c39-4e2b-a823-35df9ce41de8.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 336px;\"/>Here only two, i.e., II and IV are optically active. Since each optically active compound has two enantiomers, therefore, total <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn></math> isomeric compounds are possible.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30346,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0fbee21a-9e5c-4fc4-8266-5b3d9e61692b-image.png\" style=\"width: 139px; height: 150px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6defc4ff-f65d-4b67-bbe0-eb4db2ef6689-image.png\" style=\"width: 139px; height: 150px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/eaa56f9f-fe3f-4c7a-b8b5-a6e199a61582-image.png\" style=\"width: 141px; height: 150px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/469af007-92fc-44fc-881c-d362a7af1998-image.png\" style=\"width: 140px; height: 150px;\" /></p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The&nbsp;hydrohalogenation of alkenes&nbsp;involves breaking a carbon to carbon double bond, followed by the electrophilic addition of a hydrogen atom and halogen. The halide will add to the more substituted carbon following Markovnikov&#39;s rule.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0d105fc9-c3bc-4646-bd1c-39991febc053-image.png\" style=\"width: 166px; height: 110px;\" /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0fbee21a-9e5c-4fc4-8266-5b3d9e61692b-image.png\" style=\"width: 139px; height: 150px;\" /><br /><br />anti addition reaction.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (11 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30216,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["$b>a>c>d$","$b>a>d>c$","$a>b>d>c$","$a>b>c>d$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Reactivity in SN2 reactions with KCN depends on the stability and nucleophilicity of the transition state.<br>For benzyl halides, substituents on the benzene ring affect the reactivity of the benzylic carbon through resonance and inductive effects. <br>Para-nitro group (-NO2) is strongly electron-withdrawing, activating the benzylic carbon toward nucleophilic substitution. <br>Para-amino (-NH2) is electron-donating, deactivating. <br>Para-hydroxyl (-OH) is weakly donating. <br>Meta-nitro group has reduced electron-withdrawal compared to para-position. <br>Order of reactivity based on electronic effects: para-NO2 (c) > meta-NO2 (d) > para-OH (a) > para-NH2 (b). <br>This gives b > a > d > c","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (21 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30322,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a04bc934-be5d-428b-87cd-95bc741860f9-image.png\" style=\"width: 120px; height: 187px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9fbfceea-f5fc-4796-bec5-0f2cfaa0605c-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 193px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ab42a41f-ebee-4d26-a7b8-6f6caf53a290-image.png\" style=\"width: 120px; height: 194px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/961dcfaf-6c09-422b-8407-1441da7bc7e3-image.png\" style=\"width: 120px; height: 222px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d86b052e-87b1-4be0-9618-f3c9f301237b-image.png\" style=\"width: 323px; height: 410px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30254,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e355363f-1f1c-43cb-bb9b-f1fc2e6082af.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 148px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0ced2488-36e8-4718-af13-18be670da515.png\" style=\"width: 153px; height: 126px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3ce54e05-d485-4357-952f-41c5918ef53b.png\" style=\"width: 153px; height: 166px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ba40171b-b16b-4ce1-81a6-ab15df24eda2.png\" style=\"width: 113px; height: 190px;\" /></p>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Friedel-Crafts acylation is a reaction in which the addition of an acyl group to an aromatic ring takes place. The reaction will lead to the aromatic ring being transformed into a ketone.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9c6b210b-5828-4b6a-bcda-39021a28591b.png\" style=\"width: 293px; height: 171px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (15 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30296,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d13416be-eba7-4869-8a52-159050ab7e5e-image.png\" style=\"width: 156px; height: 171px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/62aa218f-5c18-467e-be58-9b5223728ef2-image.png\" style=\"width: 171px; height: 151px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/74da51ff-a3d3-41f0-8ebb-98b1cf6e0fd8-image.png\" style=\"width: 169px; height: 153px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3390aa2d-a05d-4b85-970b-63e1aa43dbe2-image.png\" style=\"width: 152px; height: 131px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>As compound,&nbsp;A instantly reacts with lucas reagent it should be a tertiary alcohol, and&nbsp;&nbsp;A&nbsp; a&nbsp;tertiaryl alcohol is formed by the reaction of grignard reagent,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mi>MgBr</mi></math>&nbsp;with&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>8</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>8</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>8</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>8</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>&nbsp; should be a ketone and based on the formula it can be identified as a aromatic ketone.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/27ba31ad-c681-4df3-8501-9ad33fe9e346-2018org.png\" style=\"width: 530px; height: 184px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30323,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<p><img height=\"192\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d6a55c20-3647-492d-8d33-194a595f4d23-image.png\" width=\"385\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><img height=\"199\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6b44422d-1e8c-4e1c-85f9-f47c5716b2c0-image.png\" width=\"308\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"201\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d81a936c-0e06-4153-94b8-026de79e7fe1-image.png\" width=\"332\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"142\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/22df71ee-4b2e-4c6e-be98-73a960549d3a-image.png\" width=\"313\" /></p>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5ad71fb4-5f16-4f01-9283-48ecd931e944-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 232px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30263,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["Chloral","Gammaxene","Chloropicrin","Freon-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Percentage of chlorine content =&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mtext>mass&#160;of&#160;chlorine</mtext><mtext>mass&#160;of&#160;organic&#160;compound</mtext></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>100</mn></math>&nbsp;</p><p>(A) Chloral&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>CCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CHO</mi><mo>)</mo></math>:</p><p>Percentage of chlorine content =&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>35</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>147</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>72</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>203</mn><mo>%</mo></math></p><p>(B) Gammaxene&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></math>:</p><p>Percentage of chlorine content =&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>35</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mn>291</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>73</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>%</mo></math></p><p>(C) Chloropicrin&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#8211;</mo><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>:</p><p>Percentage of chlorine content =&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>35</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mn>165</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>64</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>54</mn><mo>%</mo></math></p><p>(D) Freon-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn></math>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>CF</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></math>:</p><p>Percentage of chlorine content =&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>35</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mn>121</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>58</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>67</mn><mo>%</mo></math></p><p>As per the percentage of chlorine, Gammaxene has the maximum number of chlorine atoms.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30345,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["iii only","i and ii","i and iii","All of these"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>When given reactant reacts with the sodium methoxide solution then both substitution and elimination reactions are possible.</p><p>Substitution reaction gives the following product through&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>1</mn></msup></msub></math>&nbsp;reaction.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mn>1</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;will give the following products<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/image29-38fbee92-8e46-467c-a284-85200932d56e.jpg\" /><br /><br /><br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/135071.png\" style=\"width: 674px; height: 200px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (03 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30264,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c11b78a6-6fd4-4fc7-8034-8434efe5db73-9896229.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 182px;\" />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a4498972-dc85-487c-a910-ee456af47df0-9896229_B.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 186px;\" />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/780ebcd1-6924-484d-b2e5-c16a61e33af5-9896229_C.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 196px;\" />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e90ce1f6-667f-4e44-a9ff-3eb15d531cc1-9896229_D.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 188px;\" />&nbsp;"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Out of the three isomers of dichlorobenzene, the para-isomer is more symmetrical than the other two isomers, So, it has a more closely packed arrangement of molecules in its crystal lattice. So, para-dichlorobenzene has a higher melting point as compared to ortho and meta Isomers.</p><p>Melting point of ortho-dichlorobenzene,&nbsp;meta-dichlorobenzene&nbsp;and para-dichlorobenzene are 256K, 249K, 323K respectively.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/10d771ef-dbd0-4bd7-8843-985381ac063e-9896229.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 230px;\" /></p><p>Bromo, iodo and polychloro derivatives of hydrocarbons are heavier than water. The density increases with increase in number of carbon atoms, halogen atoms and atomic mass of the halogen atoms.</p><p>So, the correct option is D.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30242,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["Gluconic acid","Succinic acid","Oxalic acid","Malonic acid"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The ethyl bromide undergo elimination reaction with alc.KOH gives ethene.</p><p>Ethene gives dibromoethane with bromine in carbon tetra chloride. The dibromoethane converts to dicyanoethane with excess KCN. The dicyanoethane on hydrolysis gives Succinic Acid.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/48837356-4a3a-47bb-a9df-b0756ca8203d.png\" style=\"width: 755px; height: 394px;\"/></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30349,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["Claisen","Friedel-craft","Sandmeyer","Wurtz"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/LZpckKpRPTA41szf8M4gz9gyELYo96HALqu5M5Z0MSU.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\nThe above reaction is known as Sandmayer's reaction.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (12 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30303,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>(a)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/048f5f0c-8cf8-4beb-83c6-18ba3fea7141-image.png\" style=\"width: 435px; height: 70px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>(b)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dee503da-079f-4a7c-9d8e-10a81ff581ce-image.png\" style=\"width: 416px; height: 130px;\" />&nbsp;</p><p>(c)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/adeac478-9f71-4fd1-a17c-61d94a4aa792-image.png\" style=\"width: 492px; height: 120px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>The boiling points of isomeric halo alkanes decrease with increase in branching.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (06 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30367,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["$8$","$2$","$4$","$6$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\mathrm{H}_3 \\mathrm{C}-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{CH}\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)-\\mathrm{CH}_3$ on monochlorination gives\n$\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{C}(\\mathrm{Cl})-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{CH}\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)-\\mathrm{CH}_3$\n(I)\nAchiral\n$\\mathrm{H}_3 \\mathrm{C}-\\mathrm{CH}(\\mathrm{Cl})-\\mathrm{CH}\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)-\\mathrm{CH}_3$\n(II)\nChiral\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Lrx8ym_zFZqf92rd-Xa5TofLPcgoxWLI1mi981Zb1Fg.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n(III)\nAchiral<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/KTXjE5avk2BRbVr4-hOcLHi9kfhtHMV9_718H2Tn9E0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n(IV)\nchiral","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (Offline)","image":null},{"id":30387,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["pentane","isopentane","neopentane","propane"],"answer":2,"solution":"In neopentane all the $\\mathrm{H}$ atoms are same $\\left(1^0\\right)$.\n\n\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/B61-FmsYGdF-9XNtYGfX7WHV1-FXuDivzblL10BJ1jQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":30258,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;only</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced></math></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;only</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced></math>only</p><p>&nbsp;</p>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The rate of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;reaction decreases with increase in steric crowding.&nbsp;In the given set of molecules the second molecule(Tertiary alkyl halide)&nbsp;is sterically crowded, hence, it is correct option. More stable carbocation formed, higher will be the reactivity of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn></math>. Benzyl carbocation is more reactive than aliphatic carbocation.</p><p>The deactivating groups decreases the rate of electrophilic substitution reaction.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> is strong deactivating group for electrophilic substitution.</p><p>In the aromatic nucleophilic substitution reactions, the intermediate formed is carbanion and, it is stabilised by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;at ortho or para positions.</p><p>Hence <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math> all are correct.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30230,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Since 4 moles of $\\mathrm{H}_2$ is being added for complete hydrogenation the degree of unsaturation $=4$\n\nNo. of $\\pi$ electrons in $\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_6=4 \\times 2=8$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (22 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30347,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["Swarts reaction","Free radical fluorination","Sandmeyer's  reaction","Finkelstein reaction"],"answer":0,"solution":"Alkyl fluorides is best accomplished by swarts reaction i.e. heating an alkyl chloride/bromide in the presence of metallic fluoride such as AgF, Hg<sub>2</sub>F<sub>2</sub>, CoF<sub>2</sub>, SbF<sub>3</sub>.<br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>CH</mtext> <mn>3</mn> </msub> <mtext>Br</mtext> <mo>+</mo> <mtext>AgF</mtext> <mo>→</mo> <msub> <mtext>CH</mtext> <mn>3</mn></msub><mtext>F</mtext> <mo>+</mo> <mtext>AgBr</mtext> </mrow> </math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (04 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30220,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ilQ2FxerP-E7IwPRA772ZmNoSRKPj_ADaueVRcIJhaA.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/okyQnRvu7ot6QcIxFPFCblkPK1jwWod0bhi8vy7eWq0.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/opue1yF4fU47gWUQQjx3rcTP9yD-X5pPfOKNcJroeYk.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/I-1YX-Yb-UhtwLLESadUe_p5RBXpFws350JDSgRPzlA.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/scRP_esn9zCdcAlJoZa7y1ajswNvgtrxfqT_HYPKlms.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (4 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30266,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<p>(i)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Fe</mi></math></p><p>(ii)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Fe</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math></p><p>(iii)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>LiAlH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math></p>","<p>(i)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mfenced><mi>aq</mi></mfenced></math></p><p>(ii)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>LiAlH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math></p><p>(iii)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math></p>","<p>(i)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Fe</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math></p><p>(ii)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mfenced><mi>aq</mi></mfenced></math></p><p>(iii)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p>(iv)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>CuBr</mi></math></p>","<p>(i)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Fe</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math></p><p>(ii)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mfenced><mi>aq</mi></mfenced></math></p><p>(iii)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p>(iv)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>PO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>The nitro group on the benzene ring is reduced to amine group with metal and acid. Now, the methyl and nitro groups present on the benzene ring are&nbsp;ortho-para directing groups and amine group is the strong activator. Hence, bromine water reacts with respect to amino group. The amino group on the benzene ring undergoes diazotization with nitrous acid. The&nbsp;&nbsp;diazonium part reduces to benzene with hypophosphorous acid.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b95e3ca4-dc2f-4098-8658-992b0d408d8c-568b526f-fccb-4dec-97d5-d9899026630a-9895793.png\" style=\"width: 752px; height: 166px;\" />&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30374,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{RCH}_2 \\mathrm{X}>\\mathrm{R}_3 \\mathrm{CX}>\\mathrm{R}_2 \\mathrm{CHX}$","$\\mathrm{RCH}_2 \\mathrm{X}>\\mathrm{R}_2 \\mathrm{CHX}>\\mathrm{R}_3 \\mathrm{CX}$","$\\mathrm{R}_3 \\mathrm{CX}>\\mathrm{R}_2 \\mathrm{CHX}>\\mathrm{RCH}_2 X$","$\\mathrm{R}_2 \\mathrm{CHX}>\\mathrm{R}_3 \\mathrm{CX}>\\mathrm{RCH}_2 \\mathrm{X}$ \n$(\\mathrm{X}=$ a halogen $)$"],"answer":1,"solution":"More is the steric hindrance at the carbon bearing the halogen, lesser is the $\\mathrm{S}_{\\mathrm{N}} 2$ reactivity. \nHence, (B) is correct.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2007","image":null},{"id":30352,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["CH<sub>2</sub> = CH - Br + C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>5</sub> - CH<sub>2</sub>&nbsp;- ONa","C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>5</sub>&nbsp;-&nbsp;CH&nbsp;=&nbsp;CH&nbsp;- Br +&nbsp;CH<sub>3</sub>&nbsp;-&nbsp;ONa","CH<sub>2</sub><sub>&nbsp;</sub>=​&nbsp;CH&nbsp;-&nbsp;CH<sub>2</sub>&nbsp;- Br +&nbsp;C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>5</sub>ONa","C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>5</sub>Br +&nbsp;CH<sub>2</sub>&nbsp;=&nbsp;CH&nbsp;- CH<sub>2</sub>&nbsp;-&nbsp;ONa"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>It is a Williamson&#39;s ether synthesis reaction. It is a&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;reaction. Aryl halides will not undergo nucleophilic substitution reactions readily. Hence, allyl-phenyl ether can be prepared by reaction of allyl halide and phenoxide ion as follows</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9d81acde-820c-4941-bd2e-fdfcbcf50301-image.png\" style=\"width: 392px; height: 86px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30209,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["A-III, B-IV, C-I, D-II","A-I, B-II, C-IV, D-III","A-IV, B-I, C-III, D-II","A-III, B-IV, C-II, D-I"],"answer":3,"solution":"Vinyl Chloride has Cl directly attached to a C=C double bond, matching III: CH₂=CHCl. <br>Benzyl Chloride has CH₂Cl attached to a benzene ring, matching IV (benzene with CH₂Cl substituent). <br>Alkyl Chloride is a general chlorine-substituted alkane, matching II: CH₂-CH(Cl)CH₃ (a standard secondary alkyl chloride). <br>Allyl Chloride has CH₂Cl attached to the allylic position (adjacent to C=C), matching I: CH₂=CH-CH₂Cl. <br>The correct matching is A-III, B-IV, C-II, D-I.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30350,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["1-bromo-2-methylbutane","1-bromo-3-methylbutane","2-bromo-3-methylbutane","2-bromo-2-methylbutane"],"answer":3,"solution":"The order of substitution in different alkanes is\n$$\n3^{\\circ}>2^{\\circ}>1^{\\circ}\n$$\nThus the bromination of 2-methyl butane mainly gives 2-Bromo-2 - methyl butane\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/AlL06VgFamgm0nV54Nl5tltnUUl0DXeKD6d5PMn5Gmc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (12 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30343,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/image10-cf9fbf6d-64c1-4719-9d31-a61c033c28bc.jpg\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/image11-b50ed0b4-5a79-4373-8fa7-9cfd98680da3.jpg\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/image12-3c17e255-2d57-4ed9-b0df-bc098d80189e.jpg\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/image13-b75a3a57-96de-422c-b90c-c8d08fd12480.jpg\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>In presence of u.v. light allylic <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>-</mo><mo>&#160;</mo></math>bond undergoes bromination, i.e., free radical mechanism.</p><p><img height=\"195\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4fcbdaf7-14c7-4bf9-9ae0-29bad1cf723e-image.png\" width=\"576\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30259,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The intermediate formed in aromatic nucleophilic substitution reaction is carbanion. Carbanion stabilised by electron withdrawing groups. Aryl halides are less reactive towards nucleophilic aromatic substitution with aqueous <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math>. Introduction of electron releasing group like <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>OCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;group further decreases its reactivity towards nucleophilic substitution. But the introduction of electron withdrawing groups like <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;group particularly at the ortho and para position increases its reactivity towards nucleophilic substitution. Higher the number of electron withdrawing groups, higher the reactivity.<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math> The correct reactivity order is</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0f9de85c-d9da-40cc-afb6-0bb94851eda8.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 107px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30213,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["B, C and E Only","A, C and E Only","A, D and E Only","B, C and D Only"],"answer":0,"solution":"Chlorobenzene has Cl attached to an sp² carbon of the benzene ring, while chlorocyclohexane has Cl attached to an sp³ carbon.<br><br>Statement B is correct: the C-Cl bond has partial double bond character due to resonance with the aromatic π system, where chlorine's lone pairs interact with the aromatic ring.<br><br>Statement C is correct: the C-Cl bond is less polar in chlorobenzene because the resonance contribution reduces the electronegativity difference between C and Cl.<br><br>Statement E is correct: the C-Cl bond is formed using sp² hybridized orbital of carbon.<br><br>Statement A is incorrect because chlorine carries less negative charge due to resonance donation to the aromatic system.<br><br>Statement D is incorrect because the C-Cl bond is actually shorter in chlorobenzene due to partial double bond character, not longer.<br><br>The correct statements are B, C, and E only.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30290,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d437f774-7fe8-4612-bf4d-80d852361d29-image.png\" style=\"width: 258px; height: 160px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6a962810-252a-4f44-9800-4d99ab2199cc-image.png\" style=\"width: 197px; height: 154px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/40ee9436-4db4-49af-89a1-12645c58d1b2-image.png\" style=\"width: 218px; height: 158px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/73fb4861-1b81-4aa6-9bf7-265c886300e7-image.png\" style=\"width: 259px; height: 109px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4da21354-ddc2-4220-ba39-76d09a6d30d1-image.png\" style=\"width: 958px; height: 137px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30333,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/afoqaxivexvqnfcndxxjppnjvpydgxtxnjuzjphxwwptyjkdrr.jpeg\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/uahfifgzbqixkaxkomkfqjcdnnhwmicozjiultqgnwlmqfothj.jpeg\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fnhxdzkoajgaiwkmatshtyqadtmzcbrqyyqhzdmbeqjugyzbyf.jpeg\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/httxgizbikwqobeukbppxkcqsagnncssniehyzedcifahikruc.jpeg\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b9b0984d-2f3b-4868-88b1-ead79d41d6af-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 103px;\" /><br /><br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/266694.PNG\" style=\"width: 100px; height: 80px;\" />has&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>. So, elimination will take place.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (08 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30276,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3bb8fa87-e55e-4b11-a495-ff109b5f7209-image.png\" style=\"width: 140px; height: 120px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8f0dcfd1-2557-4d56-ac6c-4588a459e75c-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 120px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/312c2f6f-be24-45c7-8687-0a5dd1bdd58a-image.png\" style=\"width: 141px; height: 80px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/34959885-b4c1-46cc-b857-70422fd8de34-image.png\" style=\"width: 177px; height: 70px;\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Alpha hydrogen&nbsp;in aldehydes&nbsp;are slightly acidic and in presence of alkali they release&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>ions and carbanion.</p><p>Ethyl bromide undergoes nucleophilic substitution reaction with the carbanion generated, where bromide nucleophile&nbsp;is replaced by the carbanion&nbsp;to form ketone by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;mechansim</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2a330fe2-0064-4118-8031-777b06eebe56-12-08-2022.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 270px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30244,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d7b88608-f5bb-4cb9-972e-46e9ab22ef7e.png\" style=\"width: 444px; height: 109px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c5c7e717-c673-4e99-9b30-44737a4e92d8.png\" style=\"width: 444px; height: 112px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9b117418-d6cf-432a-93af-d2bccf90c675.png\" style=\"width: 441px; height: 111px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ad1bb8b5-f30b-45a3-aac1-061b5d031a1c.png\" style=\"width: 435px; height: 108px;\"/>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Toluene reacts with chlorine in the presence of light to give Benzal chloride. The reaction happens between methylbenzene and chlorine in the presence of ultraviolet light - typically sunlight. This is a good example of a photochemical reaction - a reaction brought about by light.</p><p>Benzyl chloride on reaction with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>/</mo><mn>373</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math> gives benzaldehyde.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cf7df457-312f-4d4f-b6ea-fda7974a8343.png\" style=\"width: 900px; height: 246px;\"/></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30307,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6abbcbce-70e1-4448-862f-5aff570a098a-image.png\" style=\"width: 217px; height: 66px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1a78c8a0-700d-46a3-89b8-2360a4f18afa-image.png\" style=\"width: 166px; height: 67px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9ccc381b-d772-4a5e-8c8d-be28910e697e-image.png\" style=\"width: 227px; height: 67px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/37231c2c-b2c8-43a3-9373-3d105ffbe83d-image.png\" style=\"width: 233px; height: 64px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Electronegativity of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></math>&nbsp;is higher than&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Br</mi></math>&nbsp;so hydrogen near to fluorine is more acidic hence it will leave in presence of base.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/89b7059f-0b52-4cc1-91b6-72022208d04a-image.png\" style=\"width: 456px; height: 142px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30234,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ufoHBX5UWfrUBmFK8BIci6dm7IAmb1fc7zaIbNhOKEs.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/k7W1bwzGCnLg1XnjrrWR-xNeh6a-qC_rpOrWAWGz9ME.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cO506-l1DmvGa-bxhUDR_7hh8mgqSFj6WO9lTb-BAeM.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fWWZSp-sJNOg0Sbfm8xuarNTvHYZL3l3-zdYzgXB1qk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/lpFBE0zLvRtjiTmFvS3m-n_YejF_mcWi_RRcaGuCR4o.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30252,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2055c171-22c8-4042-83e5-871e453b047b.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 118px;\"/>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><maction actiontype=\"argument\"><mrow></mrow></maction><mo>-</mo></msup><msub><mi>ClH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>-</mo><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>+</mo></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi>Cl</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/78470601-ab71-4cc2-bbdb-61fdb14bed0a.png\" style=\"width: 160px; height: 263px;\"/>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Substituted ammonium salt is formed when chloroalkane reacted with excess of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>, which on reaction with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math> gives <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>diaminobutane</mi></math>.</p><p>The carbon - halogen bond in alkyl halides can be easily cleaved by a nucleophile. Hence, an alkyl halide on reaction with an ethanolic solution of ammonia undergoes a nucleophilic substitution reaction in which the halogen atom is replaced by an amino group. This process of cleavage of the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>–</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></math> bond by ammonia molecule is known as ammonolysis.  Substituted ammonium salt on reaction with sodium hydroxide gives 1,4-diaminobutane as shown below,</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/08d94b82-16e7-478f-92e5-17c71760cfb9.png\" style=\"width: 700px; height: 314px;\"/></p><p>Hence, the answer is option B.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30210,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"For C₅H₁₁Br structural isomers to show optical isomerism after KOH substitution (Br→OH), the resulting product must have a chiral center (asymmetric carbon with four different groups). <br>Possible carbon skeletons: n-pentane, 2-methylbutane, 2,2-dimethylpropane. <br>Analysis of isomers: <br>2-bromopentane → CH₃CHOHCH₂CH₂CH₃: C2 bonded to H, OH, CH₃, and CH₂CH₂CH₃ (chiral). <br>3-bromopentane → CH₃CH₂CHOHCH₂CH₃: C3 bonded to H, OH, CH₂CH₃, CH₂CH₃ (NOT chiral). <br>3-bromo-2-methylbutane → CH₃CH(CH₃)CHOHCH₃: Chiral center present. <br>1-bromo-3-methylbutane → HOCH₂CH(CH₃)CH₂CH₃: C2 bonded to H, OH, CH₃, and CH₂CH₃ (chiral). <br>2,2-dimethylpropane derivatives: No chiral centers possible. <br>Compounds giving chiral products: 2-bromopentane, 3-bromo-2-methylbutane, and 1-bromo-3-methylbutane. Total = 3.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 1)","image":null}]